;Vietnamese ''<u>Vietnamese example</u>'':
{| | || ''Hôm nay'' || ''tôi'' || ''đã'' || ''ăn'' || ''bữa ăn tối''. |- | [[Chữ Nôm]]: || 𣋚𠉞 || 碎 || 吔 || 𩛖 || 𩛷𩛖啐。 |- | Gloss: || today || I || already || eat || dinner |- | Translation: ||colspan=6| I've already eaten today's dinner. |}
== Other features ==
===Politeness systems=== Linguistic systems of [[politeness]], including frequent use of [[honorific]]s, with varying levels of politeness or respect, are well-developed in Japanese and Korean. Politeness systems in Chinese are relatively weak, having simplified from a [[Chinese honorifics|more developed system]] into a much less predominant role in modern Chinese.<ref>http://www.inst.at/kctos/speakers_g-m/kadar.htm KCTOS 2007: What Happened to the Honorifics?</ref> This is especially true when speaking of the southern Chinese varieties. However, Vietnamese has retained a highly complex system of pronouns, in which the terms mostly derive from Chinese. For example, ''bác'', ''chú'', ''dượng'', and ''cậu'' are all terms ultimately derived from Chinese and all refer to different statuses of "uncle".
In many of the region's languages, including Japanese, Korean, Thai, and Malay/Indonesian, new [[personal pronoun]]s or forms of reference or address can and often do evolve from nouns as fresh ways of expressing respect or social status. Thus personal pronouns are [[open class word]]s rather than [[closed class word]]s: they are not stable over time, not few in number, and not [[clitic]]s whose use is obligatory in grammatical constructs.
With modernization and other trends, politeness language is evolving to be simpler. Avoiding the need for complex polite language can also motivate use in some situations of languages like Indonesian or English that have less complex respect systems.
